37. Bestius is introduced also by Persius VI. 37, but so as to add nothing to what we can gather from this passage. He was evidently an extravagant liver so long as his means held out, and afterwards an unsparing critic of extravagance. The character may very probably have been derived from Lucilius. All the MSS. have either correctus or corrrptns: the latter appears to give no good sense; but the former may, I think, well be interpreted ‘like Bestius after his reformation '. Lambinus asserted that he had found ‘in antiquissimo codice' corrector, and this reading, though probably only a conjecture, has been adopted by many subsequent editors. Bentley warmly defends it, quoting, with his usual readiness, several passages in which corrector is used for ‘critic’ or ‘censor ', and assuming that Bestius was a proverbially severe censor. As the reading found in all known MSS. yields a sufficiently good sense, Ι have followed Ritter and Keller in retaining it.——Maenius is of course the subject of diceret, and Bestius is in apposition, as in Vell. 41. turdo: Sat. 11. ει, 74ς 5, 10. volva: the matrix of a sow was and still is considered a great delicacy in Italy. It was prepared with spices and vinegar, and eaten as a relish with wine: Athen. ΙΙΙ. 59 ἐμπίνοντι δέ σοι φερέτω τοιόνδε τράγημα, ’γαστέρα καὶ μήτραν ἑφθὴν ὑός, ἕν τε κυμίνῳ ἕν τ’ ὀξεῖ δριμεῖ καὶ σιλφίῳ ἐμβεβαῶσαν. It was more costly than any other kind of meat commonly eaten, as Keller shows from Diocletian's edict of A. D. 301 de preliis venalium (c. iv. 3 ed. Mommsen). Prof. Palmer quotes very happily Alexis (Meineke Com. Graec. p. 738 ed. min.) ὑπὲρ πάτρας μὲν πᾶς τις ἀποθνήσκειν θέλει, ὑπὲρ δὲ μήτρας Καλλιμέδων ὁ Κάραβος ἑφθῆς ἴσως προσεῖτ’ ἄν ἄλλως ἀποθανεῖν.

46. fundata. ‘based upon ’, not quite ‘invested in’: the meaning seems to be that no man is in this case considered wise and fortunate, unless all can see from his handsome marble (nitidis) villas how firm is the basis on which his financial prosperity rests.
